{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:37:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"136"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/136"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.04,0.14,0.08,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115997"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/136"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3670"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3289"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43783"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49609"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115997","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115997"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-day history of persistent diarrhoea, consisting of four to five loose, non-bloody stools each day. Eight weeks earlier she had been hospitalised with pyelonephritis, which was treated with amoxycillin and gentamicin. This was complicated by an episode of \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E colitis, which responded to a course of oral metronidazole. However, she experienced significant nausea and only completed 10 days of the two-week course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 94/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender. Laboratory investigations reveal normal full blood count and biochemistry. \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E toxin is detected in a stool sample.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral vancomycin","Oral metronidazole","Intravenous metronidazole","Probiotic supplements","Faecal microbiota transplantation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent \u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection following incomplete treatment of her initial episode. The recurrence is likely related to both recent antibiotic exposure and inadequate duration of initial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral vancomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is now considered first-line therapy for recurrent \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection, with evidence showing superior cure rates compared to metronidazole. A typical course is 125mg four times daily for 10 days if initial infection, and 14 days duration for recurrent infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E was previously first-line therapy for mild cases but is now considered second-line due to lower cure rates and more side effects. Given this patient\u0027s previous intolerance and incomplete course, it would not be appropriate to retry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E would not achieve adequate concentrations in the bowel lumen where the infection is located. Parenteral therapy is only indicated in cases where oral therapy is impossible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProbiotic supplements\u003C/strong\u003E may have a role in preventing \u003Cem\u003EC. difficile\u003C/em\u003E infection but are not recommended as primary treatment for active infection. Evidence for their effectiveness is limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal microbiota transplantation\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients with multiple recurrences who have failed appropriate antibiotic therapy. It would be excessive for a first recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevention of future episodes should focus on antibiotic stewardship and infection control measures. The patient should be advised about the importance of completing the full course of treatment to prevent further recurrences.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vancomycin is first-line treatment for recurrent Clostridioides difficile infection.","Risk factors for Clostridioides difficile infection include recent antibiotic use and hospitalisation.","Incomplete treatment of initial infection increases risk of recurrence."],"references":["Guery B, Galperine T, Barbut F. Clostridioides difficile: diagnosis and treatments. BMJ 2019;366:l4609. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31431428/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"136"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-27T09:00:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-27T09:01:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"136"}},"con